Here's how to handle all three scenarios in .NET MAUI:

### 1. Detect the current system theme

```csharp
AppTheme currentTheme = Application.Current.RequestedTheme;
// Returns AppTheme.Light, AppTheme.Dark, or AppTheme.Unspecified
```

### 2. Subscribe to real-time theme changes

```csharp
// In App.xaml.cs or any page
Application.Current.RequestedThemeChanged += (s, e) =>
{
    AppTheme newTheme = e.RequestedTheme;
    Debug.WriteLine($"Theme changed to: {newTheme}");

    // Update UI or trigger re-theming logic here
};
```

### 3. Force a specific theme (user override)

```csharp
// Lock to dark mode regardless of system setting
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Dark;

// Lock to light mode
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Light;

// Revert to following the system setting
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Unspecified;
```

### Putting it together

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    public App()
    {
        InitializeComponent();

        Debug.WriteLine($"Current theme: {RequestedTheme}");

        RequestedThemeChanged += OnThemeChanged;
    }

    private void OnThemeChanged(object sender, AppThemeChangedEventArgs e)
    {
        Debug.WriteLine($"System theme changed to: {e.RequestedTheme}");
        // Re-apply colors, swap resources, etc.
    }

    // Call from a settings page toggle
    public void SetUserTheme(AppTheme theme)
    {
        UserAppTheme = theme; // AppTheme.Dark | .Light | .Unspecified
    }
}
```

**Key details:**

- `RequestedTheme` — read-only, reflects the OS setting.
- `UserAppTheme` — read/write, your app-level override. Set it to `Unspecified` to follow the system again.
- `RequestedThemeChanged` fires when the **system** theme changes, even if `UserAppTheme` is overriding it. Your XAML `AppThemeBinding` values only update visually when `UserAppTheme` is `Unspecified`.
- Use `AppThemeBinding` in XAML for automatic resource switching:

```xml
<Label TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=Black, Dark=White}" />
```
